<font color="#FF0000">REPLY TO CAPTAIN RAMON</font><br>
<tt>Fri Aug  8 21:44:41 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Captain Edward Ramon: It takes one helluva MAN to write a post like that. I choose to believe it too. I am deeply impressed. We both have been &quot;misbehavin'&quot; too long, for for our own selfish ego's.  <br><br>
I was never the protestor cursing veterans or spitting. I thought then, as I feel now, that I am a man of values and morality. Morality and values come in many colors. This site has helped me realize that. I hope it serves you the same.<br><br>
I have never tried to compare my two years of civilian &quot;service&quot; to the one year in the &quot;bush&quot;. That is like comparing hell and apples. I know that more now, that I did one year ago, due to this site, and the stories many have e-mailed me &quot;back channel&quot;. In fact, my whole &quot;gestalt&quot;, my understanding of Viet Nam, The Veteran, and The War, have all been twisted from my old thinking and thrust into my face for reconsideration. This site has a way of doing that, to veteran or resistor.<br><br>
I would greatly like to bury the hatchet between us (and not in one of our skulls), and acknowledge your bravery (yes, you were brave, even if the war sucked and the politicians that created it should be shot), and I do not ask for a similiar acknowledgement. I never thought becoming a conscientious objector was an act of bravery. It was the only acceptible (to me) path that I could take. Running to Canada was not me, going to jail (some draft resistors actually choose jail over war), calling veterans or soldiers foul names was not me, so becoming a C.O. and doing my bedpan duty (which I never compared to jungle duty) was to me, my way of being a good citizen during a bad war.<br><br>
We were both &quot;used and abused&quot; as you put it, just in different ways and by different folks. IF we can stop that cycle of abuse here and now, between you and I, then this site, and the goodness of &quot;real men&quot; and decent human beings, is the winner.  <br><br>
If the post above is the real Ed, than it is I that feel a sense of lose, in losing an indivdual of depth and character that I didn't get to know because we were too busy throwing rocks at each other. Clearly a warrior of class as well as grit.  If, the post above is a con, (and I really have trouble believing that), then you got me.  So what. I'll live. <br><br>
I am deeply moved by your words, and if you/we are able to move out of the parking lot and continue talking, that would really be the triumph of goodness over evil.
<p><code>-- shrink4u@mail.quik.com  (Doc Spatz) </code><p>


